<br>
<center>
<span style="font-weight: bold;">The Filipino Federation Aikido teams up with Norwegian Training Center</span>
</center>
<br>
<br><br>

Filipino Federation of Aikido and the Norwegian Training Center joins forces for ground breaking cadet program.<br><br>

The Filipino Federation of Aikido (FFA) has entered into a historic partnership with the Norwegian Training center (NTC) in the Philippines to provide a tailored aikido training program for the Norwegian Shipowners Association (NSA) cadetship program.<br><br>
 
The program, designed in accordance with the standards of the Aikido Aikikai Foundation in Japan, will be implemented at NTCâs three locations in Lyceum of the Philippines University in Batangas, University of Cebu Lapu-lapu and Mandaue in Cebu, and DMMA college of Southern Philippines in Davao.<br><br>

The partnership was formalized through a memorandum of agreement signed by representatives from both organizations.<br><br>

Representing the FFA were Royce Reyes (7th dan Aikikai) and "Billy" de Leon (6th dan Aikikai) from the Makati Aikido Club (MAC), who signed on July 28, 2025; Ma. Lourdes "Marielle" Macapawa (7th dan Aikikai) from Kannagara Dojo of Davao, who signed on August 8, 2025; and Benson Rafanan (6th dan Aikikai) from the Aikido in Cebu - Sacred Heart Aikido Center Cebu (SHACC), who signed on July 26, 2025.<br><br>
 
Representing the NSA and NTC were, Captain Knut Bentzrod, Chief Operating Officer and Larry Gonzales, NSA Cadet Manager.<br><br>

This collaboration aims to integrate aikidoâs principles of discipline, focus, and physical fitness into the training of NSA female cadets as a start, enhancing their personal development and professional readiness.<br><br>

The program is expected to commence soon, with tailored sessions designed to meet the specific needs of cadets at each NTC/NSA location. This partnership marks a significant step in fostering cross-cultural collaboration and promoting aikido as a tool for holistic training within the maritime industry.<br><br><br>

